In article <bontchev.732754211@fbihh>
bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de writes:


>> Not reading again, Vesselin? I wasn't talking about a factoring attack, but
>> a massive key generation enterprise.
>
>So what's the difference? In order to be able to factor 1024-bit
>mnumbers, your "enterprise" must generate all possible 512-bit (or
>less) primes. This is equivalent to factoring a number by brute force.
>In fact, there -are- brute-force factoring algorithms (for relatively
>small numbers only), which rely on huge collections of consecutive
>prime numbers kept on a tape. This doesn't make the method different
>from brute-force factoring - in order to be able to break -any- key,
>you must generate -all- possible 512-bit prime numbers.
>

Tut, tut, Vesselin. You know the difference between factoring primes and
using the key generation algorithm to generate RSA keys.

If you don't, then I despair of anything else you might say about mathema...
er, arithmetic.    :-)

